Notifications Module
📌 Overview

The Notifications Module is a secure, scalable component of the Enterprise Logistics Platform designed to generate and manage user notifications across multiple business events.

This module supports:

Shipment assignment alerts

Delivery status updates

Payment confirmations

Payout processing notifications

Email notifications

SMS notifications (mock implementation)

JWT-based authentication

Secure, user-scoped access control

🏗 Architecture Design

The module follows a clean, service-oriented architecture:

notifications/
│
├── models.py
├── serializers.py
├── views.py
├── urls.py
├── services.py
├── email_service.py
├── sms_service.py
Design Principles Used

Separation of concerns

Service layer pattern

Enum-based validation

JWT-based authentication

Secure user-level filtering

Extensible notification delivery system

🔐 Authentication & Security

This module uses:

djangorestframework-simplejwt

Access Token & Refresh Token mechanism

IsAuthenticated permission enforcement

Security Features

All endpoints require JWT authentication

Notifications are scoped to the logged-in user

No hardcoded user references

Enum validation prevents invalid notification types

Unauthorized access returns HTTP 401

🔔 Supported Notification Types

The module uses Django TextChoices enum to enforce strict validation.

Allowed Types:

SHIPMENT_ASSIGNED

DELIVERY_UPDATE

PAYMENT_RECEIVED

PAYOUT_PROCESSED

Invalid types are rejected with validation errors.

⚙️ Core Functionality
1️⃣ Create Notification (Service Layer)

Reusable business logic function:

create_notification(user, notification_type, reference_id=None)

This function:

Generates title & message automatically

Saves notification to database

Sends email notification

Sends SMS (mock implementation)

2️⃣ Mark Notification as Read

Users can mark notifications as read via API endpoint.

3️⃣ Email Support

Uses Django console email backend (development mode)

Automatically sends email when notification is created

Easily configurable for SMTP in production

Example Output in Console:

Subject: Payment Received
Message: Payment has been successfully received.
4️⃣ SMS Support (Mock Implementation)

SMS service prints message in console

Designed to integrate with real SMS gateway (Twilio/MSG91/etc.)

Easily extendable to production

Example Console Output:

📱 SMS SENT
To User: Arun
Message: Your payout has been processed.
🌐 API Endpoints
🔑 Authentication
Method	Endpoint	Description
POST	/api/token/	Generate JWT token
POST	/api/token/refresh/	Refresh access token
🔔 Notifications
Method	Endpoint	Description
GET	/api/notifications/	List logged-in user notifications
POST	/api/notifications/create/	Create new notification
PATCH	/api/notifications/{id}/read/	Mark notification as read
🧪 Testing Instructions
Step 1: Generate Token
POST /api/token/

Provide username & password.

Step 2: Use Bearer Token

Add in Authorization header:

Authorization: Bearer <access_token>
Step 3: Create Notification
{
    "title": "Payment Received",
    "message": "Payment for shipment #500 received",
    "type": "PAYMENT_RECEIVED",
    "reference_id": null
}
Step 4: Validate Security

Without token:

401 Unauthorized

With token:

201 Created
📊 Database Model Structure
class Notification(models.Model):

    class NotificationType(models.TextChoices):
        SHIPMENT_ASSIGNED = "SHIPMENT_ASSIGNED"
        DELIVERY_UPDATE = "DELIVERY_UPDATE"
        PAYMENT_RECEIVED = "PAYMENT_RECEIVED"
        PAYOUT_PROCESSED = "PAYOUT_PROCESSED"

Fields:

id (UUID)

user (ForeignKey)

title

message

type (Enum)

reference_id

is_read

created_at

🔄 Business Flow

When an event occurs:

System calls create_notification()

Notification is saved in DB

Email is triggered

SMS is triggered

User can view via secure API

